  "prompt": "Why do I feel sleepy and tired after consuming non-drowsy cold/flu-relief medication?",
  "response": "Feeling sleepy or tired after taking non-drowsy cold/flu relief medications can be attributed to several factors:\n\n1. **Ingredients**: While these medications are labeled as \"non-drowsy,\" they may still contain ingredients that can cause drowsiness in some individuals. For example, phenylephrine, a common decongestant, can sometimes lead to fatigue as a side effect, especially if you're sensitive to it.\n\n2. **Underlying Illness**: If you're taking cold or flu medication, your body may already be fighting off an infection. Fatigue and sleepiness are common symptoms of illness, and the medication might just be highlighting this tiredness.\n\n3. **Hydration Levels**: Cold medications may lead to dehydration, especially those that contain decongestants. Dehydration can contribute to feelings of fatigue and drowsiness.\n\n4. **Sleep Disruption**: Illness can disrupt your sleep quality. If you're experiencing sleep disturbances due to coughing, congestion, or fever, the resulting lack of rest can leave you feeling tired, even after taking medication.\n\n5. **Antihistamines**: Some cold/flu medications contain antihistamines, which are often used for their decongestant properties. Even the \"non-drowsy\" versions may still cause some level of sedation in sensitive individuals.\n\n6. **Individual Variability**: Each person's body reacts differently to medications. What is non-drowsy for most might still make some people feel sleepy.\n\nIf you continue to feel unusually tired after taking these medications, or if you have concerns about your symptoms, it may be worth consulting a healthcare provider for further evaluation.",
